  <h2>Approach</h2>
  <div class="section">
    The most effective R&D engineers solve problems by asking the right questions and building the tools to find the solution.
  </div>

  <h2>Case Study: Intermittent E-Bike System Failure</h2>

  <div class="section">
    At Specialized, I was brought into an issue where an e-bike system would intermittently shut down after ~25 hours of riding. The only error code: “No Motor.”
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    Electrical engineers had already run continuity tests, deployed CAN sniffers, and tested connection treatments with no resolution.
  </div>

  <div class="highlight">
    Instead of continuing down the same path, I reframed the problem at a system level.
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    Two patterns emerged:
    <ul>
      <li>Failure occurred only on carbon bikes, not alloy</li>
      <li>It appeared faster on certain models despite identical electronics</li>
    </ul>
    These differences pointed to mechanical influences — stiffness and suspension travel.
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    I applied an ISO 4210 structural test to a fully assembled bike and was able to consistently reproduce the electrical failure in the lab.
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    Further isolation revealed voltage fluctuations synchronized with pedal cadence. Replacing CAN sniffers with an oscilloscope exposed an unreadable CAN signal.
  </div>

  <div class="highlight">
    Root Cause: Mechanical loads altered impedance across the battery-to-bike connector, corrupting CAN communication and triggering system shutdown.
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    To quantify the issue, I designed a voltage bridge PCB to measure impedance under both lab and real-world conditions.
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    This created the first reliable method to reproduce and measure the failure, enabling rapid design iteration and validation of solutions.
  </div>

  <h2>Takeaway</h2>
  <div class="section">
    I started this project with limited experience in CAN systems. By the end, I had developed new tools, test methods, and a validated path to resolution.
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    R&D environments require the ability to enter unfamiliar problem spaces, ask better questions, and build the tools that move teams forward. That is the approach I would bring to Stryker Neurovascular.
  </div>

